Description: 

Did you know these incredible geography facts? 🌏

The United States and Australia are half a planet apart, but if you bring them closer, the west coast of Australia almost perfectly fits with the east coast of the United States!

In Europe, there's a lake in Finland called Lake Neitokainen that looks exactly like the shape of Finland itself.

The most distant point from any ocean, known as the Eurasian Pole of Inaccessibility or "EPIA," is located in China's Xinjiang region, near the border with Kazakhstan.

Hit like and subscribe for more fascinating facts! 🌍✨
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Transcript:

Here are three facts that I'm sure you didn't know:

The United States and Australia are half a planet away, but if we bring them closer, we'll see that the west coast of Australia almost perfectly fits together with the east coast of the United States.

Moving to Europe, there is a lake in Finland called Lake Neitokainen. The special thing about this lake is that it looks exactly like Finland.

The most distant point from any ocean is the Eurasian Pole of Inaccessibility, or "EPIA," and it is located in China's Xinjiang region near the border with Kazakhstan.

description:
Crispy Aloo Patties Recipe #shorts #recipe #patties #potatosnacks  #shortsfeed #potato
Recipe:-
1. For stuffing. In a pan take some chopped green chilli, 1 tbsp jeera, and 1 chopped onion. Roast it well then add 1 tbsp Kashmiri Lal mirch, 1/2 tbsp haldi, 1/2 tbsp salt and 1/2 tbsp of garam masala.
2. For dough, In a bowl take one bowl of maida along with 1/2 tbsp of salt, 2 tbsp of oil and water.
3. Make a soft dough.
4. Take small portion and roti nd fold it as shown and apply oil and dust maida.
5. Add the stuffing and roll as shown.
6. Fry in low heat oil until it becomes crispy.
7. Your tasty aloo patties is ready.. Enjoy..❤️

title: I dunno why but this video makes me so emotional #shorts #fashiondesigner #fashion #fashiondesign
description:
Ugh. This was supposed to be a trend. Not make me emotional. But my eyes are hurting from the tears I’m trying to push back in. 

This is my sketch book from 6th grade. I drew for fun when I wasnt doing homework, studying or playing tennis. I designed dresses for my Barbie’s, dance recitals, Halloween, and even my friend’s prom dress later on in high school. All I EVER wanted was to be a fashion designer.

My parents suppressed my dreams, in hopes of saving me from a risky career, but back then, it completely broke our relationship. I felt so lost, hollow, and purposeless. I had so much anger in my heart for them. 

I ended up sabotaging myself so I couldn’t take the MCAT, but still graduated with a degree in Biology, lived a short life in corporate fashion, took random Craigslist jobs, was an eBayer for a sec, taught Pilates on YouTube (while they were constantly asking “when are going back to school?”), and now…

*sigh*

I’m just so grateful. I can’t believe I’m getting to live little Cassey’s dream.

♥️Big Cassey
CEO + Head Designer of @popflexactive and @blogilates

title: Travelling on your Period can feel like this - IYKYK! #tanyakhanijowshorts #travel #travelshorts
description:
I’ve been experiencing some weird period cycles off late.



I’ve mostly been extremely moody. I know it’s TMI, but I think it definitely has everything to do with my travels and not having a home base.


On some days, it does get stressful and it’s only been 4 months of doing this. I have not stayed at any one place for more than 10 days! And I honestly just realised that while typing! 😱


This is from my last trip to Mussoorie, where I stayed for good 7 days without filming any videos.


Also, I’m not complaining, just sharing my observations for no good reason. Lol!


If you made it till here, I’m sorry for wasting your time. 🤡

title: The CRAZIEST Day Of School EVER! 😱 #shorts #storytime
What's the wildest thing you've seen a parent allow? #redditstories #storytime #shorts
description:
I witnessed something at my local library that changed how I see the world.

It was a rainy Tuesday afternoon when I went to return some books. The children's section was busier than usual because of the weather, with kids sprawled on colorful bean bags while parents chatted nearby.

That's when I noticed them – a thin boy about eight years old with a stack of books beside him, and his dad sitting across from him. Nothing strange at first, until I realized the boy hadn't turned a page in over twenty minutes.

He was just staring at the same page, his finger tracing the words over and over. The dad would occasionally lean over, point to a word, and wait. The boy would struggle, his face scrunching up with effort, then whisper something. His dad would either nod or gently shake his head.

I found a seat nearby and pretended to read while watching this painfully slow process. Other kids zipped through colorful picture books while this boy fought for every single word.

After an hour, they only made it through six pages. The librarian walked by and smiled warmly at them. "Back again, you two? Fourth day this week!"

That's when I noticed the boy's clothes – the same faded blue shirt he'd worn yesterday when I'd been here. His sneakers had holes near the toes.

When the library announced closing time, the dad carefully marked their place with a receipt and closed the book. The boy looked devastated. "But Dad, we didn't finish Harry's adventure today."

His dad knelt down. "We'll pick up tomorrow where we left off, buddy. Promise."

The boy looked at the book longingly. "I wish we could take it home."

"I know," his dad said quietly. "Maybe next month."

As they walked toward the exit, I overheard the librarian ask, "Still no luck with the job search?"

The dad shook his head. "Three interviews this week, but nothing yet. We're okay though."

The next day, I arrived early with a plan. I spotted them in the same corner and approached cautiously. "Excuse me," I said. "I work with a children's literacy program. We're giving away book club memberships and your son was recommended by the staff here."

The dad looked surprised. "Really?"

I nodded, trying to sound official. "It includes a library card with all fees covered for a year, and one book to keep each month."

The boy's eyes widened. "My own books? To keep forever?"

"That's right," I said, pulling out a gift card I'd bought that morning. "This covers everything. You just need to sign this form." I handed over a made-up application.

The dad studied it carefully. I could see the pride fighting with necessity in his eyes. "This is very generous, but—"

"Dad, please!" the boy whispered. "I could practice at home too!"

Something in his father's expression broke. He signed the paper and handed it back to me.

For three weeks, I saw them every afternoon. The boy carefully chose a new book each week, and his reading improved noticeably. His dad found occasional day labor that paid cash. Things seemed to be looking up.

Then one day, they didn't show up. Or the next day. Or the day after that.

A week later, I found the librarian sorting books. "Have you seen the man with his son? The ones who come in to read every day?"

Her face fell. "You didn't hear? There was a fire in their building last night. One of those old apartment complexes without proper alarms."

My heart stopped. "Are they okay?"

She shook her head. "The dad didn't make it out. They said he went back in for something. The boy's in the hospital with smoke inhalation, but he'll survive."

I felt sick. "What will happen to him?"

"No other family that we know of. Child services is involved."

The next morning, I went to the hospital. I didn't know the boy's full name, so I just described him to the nurses. One recognized him and reluctantly let me visit for five minutes.

He was small in the hospital bed, oxygen tubes in his nose. On the table beside him was a charred, water-damaged copy of Harry Potter. The book they'd been reading together.

"Your dad went back for the book," I whispered, understanding hitting me like a punch.

The boy nodded, his eyes hollow. "He promised we'd finish it." His voice was raspy from the smoke.

I sat with him, my heart breaking as he opened the damaged book. Most pages were ruined, but he turned to page 189 - exactly where they'd left off that last day at the library.

I started reading where his father would never get to. The boy closed his eyes, tears streaming down his face.

Two days later, they transferred him to a group home. I tried to visit, but they wouldn't let me in. "Family only," they said.

I left my number with the staff. "Please, just give him this message: I'll keep the book safe until he can finish it."

A month passed. Then two. I visited the group home weekly, but they always turned me away.

One cold morning, I found a small package at my door. Inside was the burned copy of Harry Potter and a note from a social worker:
